      "writtenOn": "2026-03-12T02:39:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not sure how to reconcile your suggestion with the next sentence and the goals here.  You wrote:\n\n\u003e What if we change to \"If maintainers want to enable a new check, they should first open a review to add it to this list to begin a discussion\". I don\u0027t want a docs MERGE to be a requirement, but sure, opening a review is reasonable.\n\nTo me that means someone can just propose a change here and merge it in their repo (without any feedback).  I don\u0027t really know how that solves anything.\n\nThe next sentence states:\n\n\u003e If a new `clang-tidy` check is useful, a change to the reference is sufficient and should not have much friction.\n\nThat\u0027s the goal: low friction for new changes.  I don\u0027t think 82879 is a good example because if we were driving to consensus well on the dependent commit, I think we\u0027d just power through the unresponsive feedback (or at least the proposer could ask that we just move forward and I think we should honor that).\n\nI do think it is reasonable:\n  1. make a fix/enable change in one or more repos and push a pending commit to Gerrit to show viability\n  2. make the proposal here\n  3. merge (1) once (2) has consensus.\n\nA later commit here \"catches\" us up to clang-21.  I guess we could make a prereq for a new clang version that we go through and make a disposition on each new clang-tidy warning... do we want to do that?",
